    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the difference between a pet microchip and a GPS tracker?</summary>
        <p>A microchip is an implant the size of a grain of rice that contains an ID number; it must be physically scanned by a vet or shelter and cannot track a pet's location. A GPS tracker is a wearable device on a collar that uses satellites and cellular data to transmit the pet's live location to your smartphone.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can I track my dog with just a microchip?</summary>
        <p>No. Microchips do not emit a signal, have no battery, and do not use GPS. They rely on Radio-Frequency Identification (RFID), which only activates when a scanner is held inches away from the pet. They are purely for identification, not location tracking.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Are Apple AirTags good for tracking lost pets?</summary>
        <p>AirTags can be useful in densely populated urban areas, as they rely on pinging nearby iPhones via Bluetooth to update their location. However, they do not use true GPS. If your pet gets lost in a rural area or the woods away from people with smartphones, an AirTag will not be able to update its location.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why do GPS pet trackers require a monthly subscription?</summary>
        <p>While the tracker uses free satellite signals to determine its location, it must use cellular networks (like 4G or 5G LTE) to transmit that location data over the internet to the app on your phone. The subscription fee pays for the device's cellular data plan.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What should I do first if my pet goes missing?</summary>
        <p>Immediately update your pet's microchip registry to flag them as lost and ensure your contact info is current. Then, use online community pet finder networks and social media to alert neighbors. If you have a GPS collar, activate its "live tracking" or "lost dog" mode to increase the frequency of location updates.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
